---
import BaseHead from "../../../components/BaseHead.astro";
import Header from "../../../components/Header.astro";
import Footer from "../../../components/Footer.astro";
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <BaseHead
      title="JavaScript — Learning Notes"
      description="My consolidated learning notes while understanding JavaScript from fundamentals to advanced concepts."
    />
  </head>

  <body>
    <Header />

    <main>
      <article>
        <h1>JavaScript</h1>

        <p class="status in-progress">
          Status: In progress
        </p>
        <p class="note-disclaimer">
            These are my personal learning notes. They reflect how I currently
            understand Git and GitHub and may evolve as I use them more.
        </p>        

        <!-- WHY -->
        <section>
          <h2>Why I’m learning JavaScript</h2>
          <p>
            JavaScript sits at the center of everything I want to build on the web.
            I didn’t want shallow knowledge, so I decided to understand it
            layer by layer — not just syntax, but how it actually works.
          </p>
        </section>

        <!-- FUNDAMENTALS -->
        <section>
          <h2>Foundations that clicked</h2>
          <ul>
            <li>Difference between <code>const</code>, <code>let</code>, and why <code>var</code> is avoided</li>
            <li>Primitive data types and how JavaScript treats values</li>
            <li>Writing small functions instead of repeating logic</li>
            <li>Using arrays and objects as the basic containers of data</li>
            <li>Loops as tools, not default solutions</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <!-- DOM -->
        <section>
          <h2>Understanding the DOM (browser interaction)</h2>
          <p>
            The DOM finally made sense when I stopped seeing it as “magic”
            and started seeing it as a tree built from HTML.
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li><code>querySelector</code> as the main way to grab elements</li>
            <li>Changing text with <code>textContent</code></li>
            <li>Using <code>classList</code> instead of inline styles</li>
            <li>Handling user actions with <code>addEventListener</code></li>
            <li>Creating and removing elements dynamically</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <!-- MINI PROJECT -->
        <section>
          <h2>Mini project that helped</h2>
          <p>
            Building a simple To-Do List clarified many concepts:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>Event delegation</li>
            <li>DOM updates based on state</li>
            <li>Why structure matters more than clever code</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <!-- ES6 -->
        <section>
          <h2>Modern JavaScript (ES6+)</h2>
          <ul>
            <li>Arrow functions for cleaner function syntax</li>
            <li>Template literals instead of string concatenation</li>
            <li>Destructuring objects and arrays</li>
            <li>Spread vs rest operators</li>
            <li>Using <code>map</code>, <code>filter</code>, and <code>reduce</code> instead of manual loops</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <!-- ASYNC -->
        <section>
          <h2>Asynchronous JavaScript (big mental shift)</h2>
          <p>
            This was the hardest part conceptually.
            Understanding that JavaScript is single-threaded but non-blocking
            changed how I reason about code.
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>Event loop: stack, queue, and Web APIs</li>
            <li>Why callbacks become unreadable</li>
            <li>Promises as a cleaner abstraction</li>
            <li>Async / await as the readable standard</li>
            <li>Using <code>fetch</code> and handling errors properly</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <!-- UNDER THE HOOD -->
        <section>
          <h2>Under the hood concepts</h2>
          <ul>
            <li>Scope (global, function, block)</li>
            <li>Closures as functions carrying their environment</li>
            <li>How <code>this</code> changes with context</li>
            <li>Why arrow functions behave differently</li>
            <li>Prototypes and how methods actually exist</li>
            <li>Classes as a cleaner syntax over prototypes</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <!-- ECOSYSTEM -->
        <section>
          <h2>The JavaScript ecosystem</h2>
          <ul>
            <li>Node.js to run JavaScript outside the browser</li>
            <li>npm as the package manager</li>
            <li>Why frameworks exist (React, Vue, Angular)</li>
            <li>Why Git is non-negotiable</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <!-- CONFUSIONS -->
        <section>
          <h2>Things that still confuse me</h2>
          <ul>
            <li>Deep async edge cases</li>
            <li>Advanced prototype chains</li>
            <li>Performance implications of different patterns</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <!-- NEXT -->
        <section>
          <h2>What I’ll focus on next</h2>
          <ul>
            <li>Building more projects with vanilla JS</li>
            <li>React fundamentals</li>
            <li>Using APIs in real apps</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <!-- NAV -->
        <nav class="note-nav">
          <a href="/learning-paths/notes/html-css">← HTML-CSS</a>
          <a href="/learning-paths/notes/git-github">Git & GitHub →</a>
        </nav>

      </article>
    </main>

    <Footer />
  </body>
</html>
